T1  - International R&D competition and trade policy
AU  - Clemenz, Gerhard
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 93
EP  - 113
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(90)90051-M
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969090051M
AB  - R&D is modelled as a costly random draw from a set of technologies for producing a homogeneous good. It is shown that free trade stimulates R&D as compared to autarky by increasing competition and the market size, both leading to higher expected returns to R&D. If the technological gap is too wide, however, socially beneficial R&D may be discouraged in the technologically inferior country. In this case complete protection can be better than free trade, but it is inferior to other policies like tariffs or, in particular, direct subsidies to R&D.
ER  - 

